<subSubSection lastPageId="34" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1591,2028]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,319,1628,1654]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species, not previously recorded north of Florida, is represented in the SAB by a single specimen collected from offshore 
<collectingCountry box="[552,650,1666,1692]" name="Georgia" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Georgia</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duchassaing" authorityYear="1870" box="[661,801,1666,1691]" class="Anthozoa" family="Anthothelidae" genus="Iciligorgia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="schrammi">
<emphasis box="[661,801,1666,1691]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">I. schrammi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered a deep reef species in tropical latitudes, but the examined specimen has no associated habitat data.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1591,2028]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
The specimen is dichotomously branched in one plane, and the main branches appear flattened and are 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3– 5 mm</quantity>
in width. The colony examined is relatively small, as this species tends to form very large, planar structures in southern latitudes. Because no definite base is attached to the stem it is not known if the specimen is complete. The color is light brown, but this species has been reported to be bright red in life (
<bibRefCitation author="Cairns, S." box="[159,309,1890,1916]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refId="ref25011" refString="Cairns, S. (1977) Guide to the commoner shallow-water gorgonians (sea whips, sea feathers, and sea fans) of Florida, the Gulf of Mexico, and the Caribbean region. University of Miami, Miami, Florida, 74 pp." type="book" year="1977">Cairns 1977</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Humann, P." box="[323,497,1890,1916]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refId="ref26006" refString="Humann, P. (1993) Reef coral identification: Florida, Caribbean, Bahamas, including marine plants. New World Publications, Jacksonville, Fl, 239 pp." type="book" year="1993">Humann 1993</bibRefCitation>
). The polyps are arranged biserially along the two edges of the flattened stem. Most polyps are visible and substantially armed with curved spindles and rods arranged as collaret and points (
<figureCitation box="[159,309,1964,1990]" captionStart="FIGURE 32" captionStartId="34.[151,255,1625,1649]" captionTargetBox="[226,1345,421,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-170@34.[226,1360,421,1604]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 32. Iciligorgia schrammi (S2697, preserved specimen): A, sclerites; a–c) spindles from cortex; d–e) needles from medulla (scale bar = 0.1 mm); B, colony with attached ophiuroids (height approximately 13 cm); C, fistulose branch; D, anthocodia showing orientation of collaret and points." pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figure 32D</figureCitation>
). Calyces are domelike and have eight distinct lobes. The fistulose branches (
<figureCitation box="[1283,1428,1964,1990]" captionStart="FIGURE 32" captionStartId="34.[151,255,1625,1649]" captionTargetBox="[226,1345,421,1604]" captionTargetId="figure-170@34.[226,1360,421,1604]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 32. Iciligorgia schrammi (S2697, preserved specimen): A, sclerites; a–c) spindles from cortex; d–e) needles from medulla (scale bar = 0.1 mm); B, colony with attached ophiuroids (height approximately 13 cm); C, fistulose branch; D, anthocodia showing orientation of collaret and points." pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figure 32C</figureCitation>
) distinguish this species from any other in the shallow western Atlantic.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="34.[151,1436,152,364]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
The cortical sclerites are chiefly elongate, spiny spindles 0.5–0.6 mm in length, varying in coarseness. The medullar sclerites are long (0.5–0.7 mm), extremely slender needles that vary from smooth to slightly warty. The anthocodiae have flattened, slightly curved rods up to 0.5 mm, with a few that are a fraction of that size. This specimen is associated with numerous small gorgonocephalid ophiuroids. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,467,301,327]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Atlantic distribution:</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[477,574,301,327]" name="Georgia" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Georgia</collectingCountry>
, south Florida to 
<collectingCountry box="[790,865,301,327]" name="Brazil" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, Caribbean, 
<quantity box="[1018,1124,301,327]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.855" metricValueMax="3.6799999999999997" metricValueMin="0.03" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" unit="m" value="185.5" valueMax="368.0" valueMin="3.0">3–368 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Deichmann, E." box="[1142,1351,301,327]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" refId="ref25431" refString="Deichmann, E. (1936) The Alcyonaria of the western part of the Atlantic Ocean. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 53, 317 pp." type="book" year="1936">Deichmann 1936</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bayer, F. M." pageId="34" pageNumber="35" pagination="1 - 373" refId="ref24655" refString="Bayer, F. M. (1961) The shallow-water Octocorallia of the West Indian region. A manual for marine biologists. Studies on the Fauna of Curacao and other Caribbean Islands, 12, 1 - 373." type="journal article" year="1961">Bayer 1961</bibRefCitation>
; NMNH collections; SERTC collection).
</paragraph>
